## Diagnosis

The clipping is a **native `<input>` line-box confinement problem**, not a padding problem. Here is what is happening structurally:

### Why `padding-top` makes it taller without fixing the clip

A `<input type="text">` (and `<textarea>`) renders text through the UA's native text engine, not through CSS box-model flow. The browser:

1. Allocates a **internal text rectangle** whose height is: `line-height × 1` (single-line) or `line-height × rows` (textarea)
2. Centers the text vertically within that rectangle using its own font-metric baseline algorithm
3. **Clips the text to the internal text rectangle** — not to the element's padding box

When `padding-top` grows, the *element* gets taller but the *internal text rectangle* stays the same size and in the same vertical position relative to the `em` square. The cap-height of a display serif at 4xl–6xl already overflows the top of the `em` square (because the browser clips to the *content edge*, not the *ink bounds*), so the ascenders are clipped against a ceiling that `padding-top` has no influence over.

**Root cause: AP-064 / EAP-077.** The `<input>` element's built-in overflow model is incompatible with display-scale serif fonts. IBM Plex Serif's cap-height at 4xl–6xl fluid (`clamp(36px, …, 60px)`) exceeds the em square, and the UA clips paint to the content region. No CSS property on the `<input>` itself escapes this — the fix requires replacing the `<input>` with a `contentEditable` div so the text is rendered in the normal CSS box-model where `overflow: visible` is the default.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-064** — *Native `<input>` Text Rendering for Display-Scale Serif Fonts*
**EAP-077** — *Assuming CSS Can Fix `<input>` Native Text Clipping for Oversized Serif Fonts*

The `introBlurbHeadline` editor field is still a native `<input>` or `<textarea>` styled with `@include heading-case-study-intro` (IBM Plex Serif, 4xl–6xl fluid). At these sizes, the glyph ink of IBM Plex Serif's caps and ascenders overshoots the top of the CSS `em` square. The `<input>` UA engine clips paint to the element's content edge, not the glyph's actual ink bounds. `padding-top` moves the element boundary but the clip plane follows it — the glyph is still clipped.

The same bug already existed on the Login page (`<input type="password">` at 2.75rem serif) and was resolved there (ENG-139, FB-129) by swapping to a `contentEditable` wrapper.

---

## Fix

### 1. Replace `<input>` / `<textarea>` with a `contentEditable` div

**File:** `src/components/inline-edit/display-scale-title-input.tsx` *(or wherever the case-study editor's title field lives — adjust path below to match your actual file)*

The canonical pattern (established for the Login field in ENG-139):

```tsx
// display-scale-title-input.tsx
'use client'

import { useRef, useEffect } from 'react'
import styles from './display-scale-title-input.module.scss'

interface Props {
  value: string
  onChange: (value: string) => void
  placeholder?: string
}

export function DisplayScaleTitleInput({ value, onChange, placeholder }: Props) {
  const ref = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null)

  // Sync incoming value without clobbering cursor position
  useEffect(() => {
    const el = ref.current
    if (!el) return
    // Only reset DOM text when it actually differs from state
    // (prevents cursor-jumping on every keystroke)
    if (el.textContent !== value) {
      el.textContent = value
    }
  }, [value])

  return (
    <div
      ref={ref}
      role="textbox"
      aria-multiline="false"
      aria-label="Case study title"
      contentEditable
      suppressContentEditableWarning
      data-placeholder={placeholder}
      className={styles.titleInput}
      onInput={(e) => {
        onChange((e.currentTarget as HTMLDivElement).textContent ?? '')
      }}
      onKeyDown={(e) => {
        // Single-line semantics: Enter saves, not inserts newline
        if (e.key === 'Enter') {
          e.preventDefault()
          ref.current?.blur()
        }
      }}
    />
  )
}
```

**Key structural differences from `<input>`:**

| Property | `<input>` | `contentEditable div` |
|---|---|---|
| Text rendering engine | UA native (clips to content edge) | CSS normal flow (overflow: visible by default) |
| `padding-top` effect on clip | None — clip plane follows | Works correctly — ink is never clipped |
| `line-height` control | Partial (ignored in Blink for single-line) | Full — both spacing and clip boundary |
| `overflow` default | `hidden` internally, un-overridable | `visible` — glyphs can freely overshoot |
| Multi-line behaviour | Requires `<textarea>` | Same element, `white-space: nowrap` for single-line |

### 2. SCSS module for the contentEditable field

**File:** `src/components/inline-edit/display-scale-title-input.module.scss`

```scss
@use 'src/styles/mixins/typography' as *;
@use 'src/styles/tokens/spacing' as *;

.titleInput {
  @include heading-case-study-intro;  // IBM Plex Serif, 4xl–6xl fluid, leading 1.25

  // The critical fix: give the line box room to breathe above cap-height.
  // IBM Plex Serif's cap-height at 60px is ~42px; the em square top is ~48px;
  // the ascender overshoots by ~6–8px at max scale.
  // line-height: 1.25 already provides internal spacing, but the container
  // needs explicit vertical padding so the overflow is visible, not clipped.
  padding-block: $portfolio-spacer-1x;

  // Ensure no ancestor introduces overflow: hidden on this element.
  overflow: visible;

  // Single-line semantics
  white-space: nowrap;
  overflow-x: auto;   // let long titles scroll rather than wrap

  // Cursor and interaction
  outline: none;
  cursor: text;

  // Empty-state placeholder via data attribute
  &:empty::before {
    content: attr(data-placeholder);
    color: var(--portfolio-text-placeholder);
    pointer-events: none;
  }

  // Focus ring (inherits from the DS Input engaged-state token, AP-054)
  &:focus-visible {
    box-shadow: 0 0 0 1px var(--portfolio-border-focus);
  }
}
```

### 3. Audit the ancestor stack for `overflow: hidden` (EAP-080)

The second way this clip can re-appear is an ancestor with `overflow: hidden`. After the swap, check your editor layout:

```tsx
// In the case-study editor wrapper — look for this pattern and fix it:

// ❌ BEFORE (causes glyph clip on the contentEditable child)
<div className={styles.titleRow}>   {/* overflow: hidden here? */}
  <DisplayScaleTitleInput ... />
</div>

// ✅ AFTER — use clip-path or overflow: clip on a separate clipping wrapper
// that sits OUTSIDE the title input's line box, not around it.
```

If you need to clip a *row* (e.g., to prevent horizontal scroll bleeding into the sidebar), wrap a separate clipping div *outside* the `DisplayScaleTitleInput`, keeping the title's immediate parent as `overflow: visible`:

```tsx
// Separate the clipping concern from the text container:
<div className={styles.titleClip}>      {/* overflow: hidden lives HERE */}
  <div className={styles.titlePadded}>  {/* padding-block here, overflow: visible */}
    <DisplayScaleTitleInput ... />
  </div>
</div>
```

```scss
.titleClip {
  overflow: hidden;
  // Do NOT put this class directly on the element containing display-scale text.
}

.titlePadded {
  // Must have enough padding that glyph overshoot falls within this box,
  // not clipped by .titleClip above.
  padding-block: $portfolio-spacer-1x;
  overflow: visible;
}
```

---

## What's Structurally Different About Display-Scale Fonts in Inputs

Here is the complete mental model so this is clear permanently:

### 1. The `em` square vs. ink bounds

Every glyph sits inside an **em square** — a theoretical bounding box defined by the font's UPM (Units Per Measure). CSS `font-size: 60px` allocates a 60px em square. But display serif typefaces (IBM Plex Serif, Georgia, etc.) are designed with **ink that intentionally overflows the em square**: tall caps, deep descenders, and swash terminals all exceed the theoretical box. At body scale (14–18px), this overflow is a few pixels and is rarely visible. At display scale (36–60px), the overshoot is 6–12px and is immediately visible as clipping.

### 2. Why `<input>` clips when `<div>` doesn't

The browser's UA stylesheet sets `overflow: hidden` internally on the text-rendering sub-engine of `<input>` and `<textarea>`. This is not a CSS rule you can override — it's part of the native widget implementation. The rendered text is composited inside an internal layer whose bounds are the *content edge* of the element (i.e., after padding is applied, but the clip is against the em-square boundary, not the ink boundary). No CSS property on the `<input>` changes this clip plane.

A `contentEditable div`, by contrast, renders text through the same engine as all other CSS block flow. `overflow: visible` is its default and it means what it says: ink that overflows the em square is visible, not clipped.

### 3. Why `line-height` doesn't save you on `<input>`

On a `<div>`, setting `line-height: 1.4` makes the line box 1.4× the em square, which pushes the logical top of the line box above the ink's top edge — the ink no longer clips. On a single-line `<input>`, Blink/WebKit recalculates the line box to *exactly fit the content height* regardless of your `line-height` value. The value is partially respected for text positioning but the clip boundary is reset to the content edge. This is why neither `padding-top` nor `line-height: 2` fixes it on `<input>`.

### 4. The `padding-top` trap

When you increase `padding-top` on an `<input>`:
- The element grows taller ✓
- The padding area grows ✓  
- The text rectangle *stays anchored* to the top of the content area ✗  
- The clip plane moves with the content edge, not with the ink ✗  

The glyph ascender is still being clipped by the same ceiling; the ceiling just moved down by the padding amount — but so did the text. Net result: zero change to the clip, bigger input.

### 5. The canonical solution (documented in AP-064, EAP-077)

Any display-scale (≥ 3xl / 30px) serif text that needs to be editable **must** use a `contentEditable` div, never a native `<input>`. The checklist:

- `contentEditable` div with `role="textbox"`
- `white-space: nowrap` for single-line semantics
- `overflow: visible` (explicit, to resist being overridden by inherited styles)
- `padding-block` ≥ `$portfolio-spacer-1x` so the line-box breathing room is visible
- No `overflow: hidden` on the immediate parent (use EAP-080's split-wrapper pattern if clipping is needed higher up)

---

## Principle

> **AP-064 / EAP-077:** A native `<input>` clips display-scale serif glyphs at the UA level — no CSS property escapes it. The structural fix is always a `contentEditable` div: it renders through normal CSS flow where `overflow: visible` is real and `padding-block` actually moves the clip plane. The symptom "padding makes it taller but not unclipped" is the diagnostic signature of this anti-pattern — when you see it, don't increase padding further, swap the element.
